  "text": "The most striking factor in the I-S reaction is its dependence on temperature. Time is also an important factor in the diagenetic reaction of I-S. In the Gulf Coast region, for instance, the younger rocks have obviously not changed as much as the old ones, which suggests that the smectite-to-illite reaction is kinetically controlled as a function of time. Based on temperature and geological age, [CITATION_1] proposed time-temperature models for I-S geothermal studies. The conversion of(R = 0) I-S to (R = 1) I-S is assigned to 100-110~ for sedimentary rocks of Miocene age or older (5-300 Ma) (Hoffman and Hower model; [CITATION_2] . For younger rocks (<3 Ma), however, the I-S conversion is at a higher temperature of 120-140~ (short-life geothermal model; [CITATION_3] . In the SSK-1D well, (R = 0) I-S transforms at -3200 m where corrensite occurs; (R = 1) I-S is found at <3200 m. Therefore, the conversion of (R = 0) I-S to (R = 1) I-S is estimated to occur at a depth of 3200 m. If the ttoffman and Hower model is applied to the conversion, the depth of 3200 m is assigned to 100M 10~ However, if the short-life model is applied, the same depth can be assigned to 120-140~",
